          "type": "user",
          "text": "# AGENTS.md instructions for /Users/daniel/Documents/GitHub/browser-extension\n\n<INSTRUCTIONS>\n# Agent Instructions\n\n## Git Workspaces\n\nCheckout new repos to `~/Documents/GitHub` by default.\n\n### Agent Skills\n\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/agent-skills` — Claude Code, Codex skills, symlinked into `~/.claude/skills/` and `~/.codex/skills/`\n\n### Rainbow Workspace\n\n#### Wallet Frontends\n\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/rainbow` — Rainbow App (React Native, Mobile, iOS/Android)\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/browser-extension` — Rainbow BX / Rainbow Browser Extension (React, Chrome/Firefox)\n\n#### SDKs\n\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/rainbow-provider` — EIP-1193 Ethereum Provider for BX and Dapp Browser (`@rainbow-me/provider`)\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/rainbow-swaps` — Swaps SDK (`@rainbow-me/swaps`)\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/rainbow-delegation` — EIP-7702 Delegation SDK (`@rainbow-me/delegation`)\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/stores` — Zustand Stores (`@storesjs/stores`, used across repos)\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/calibur` — Uniswap Calibur contract\n\n#### RainbowKit\n\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/rainbowkit` — RainbowKit monorepo\n  - `@rainbow-me/rainbowkit`\n  - `@rainbow-me/rainbow-button`\n  - `@rainbow-me/rainbowkit-siwe-next-auth`\n\n#### Dependencies\n\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/ox` — ox ([oxlib.sh](https://oxlib.sh))\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/viem` — viem ([viem.sh](https://viem.sh))\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/wagmi` — wagmi ([wagmi.sh](https://wagmi.sh))\n- `~/Documents/GitHub/ethers` — wagmi ([ethers](https://docs.ethers.org/v4/))\n\n#### Repo Aliases\n\nThese repos are worked in daily. Resolve these terms to the correct repo without asking for clarification:\n\n- **\"the app\"**, **\"mobile\"**, **\"mobile app\"** → `rainbow`\n- **\"BX\"**, **\"the extension\"**, **\"browser extension\"** → `browser-extension`\n- **\"Query Store\"**, **\"Derived Store\"** → `stores`\n\n## Git & Graphite Workflow\n\n### Commit Descriptions\n\nEvery commit must include a description body (not just a subject line, and not a PR description). Always follow these rules:\n\n1. **Lead with the goal** — one sentence explaining what behavior is being added, changed, or fixed and why.\n2. **Describe the implementation** — cover all meaningful code changes (new logic, modified control flow, new imports/exports, store interactions). Group related changes rather than listing every line. Skip boilerplate (import reordering, formatting).\n3. **Behavior changes** — explicitly state what changes from the user's perspective. Describe the before and after: what previously happened vs. what happens now. If a UI element moves, a flow changes, or a default value shifts, call it out.\n4. **Intended side effects** — document any deliberate side effects: new network requests, changes to persisted state, new event emissions, modified lifecycle behavior, or altered timing/ordering. If there are no intended side effects, do not mention this.\n5. **Test coverage** — list every new or modified test case individually. For each test, state the scenario being tested and what the test asserts/guarantees. Be specific about edge cases, error paths, and boundary conditions covered.\n6. **Keep it purely technical** — state what the code does. No marketing language or organizational framing.\n7. **On squash** — when multiple commits are squashed, unify into a single description covering the final state of all changes. Do not list individual commits.\n8. **No line length limit** — do not wrap or break lines in the commit body. Absolutely no line breaks.\n\n### Co-Authored-By\nDo not append a `Co-Authored-By` trailer to commit messages.\n\n### Pushing & Submitting\n**NEVER push or submit without explicit written confirmation from the user.** This applies to:\n- `git push` (any branch, any remote)\n- `git push --force` / `git push -f`\n- `gh pr create` / `gh pr merge`\n- `gt submit` / `gt stack submit`\n- Any other command that sends local changes to a remote\n\nDo not infer permission from prior context. Each push/submit requires its own explicit approval.\n\nWhen submitting with Graphite, always use `gt submit --no-interactive --ai` so that Graphite generates the PR title and description.\n\n### Branch Naming Convention\nWhen creating new branches, use this format:\n- Prefix: `@daniel/` (always use the @ symbol)\n- Pattern: `@daniel/<commit-type>-<brief-description>`\n- First segment after prefix **must match conventional commit format** (feat, fix, docs, chore, refactor, test, etc.)\n- Keep names **concise and clear**\n\n**Examples:**\n- ✅ `@daniel/feat-auth-provider`\n- ✅ `@daniel/fix-login-bug`\n- ✅ `@daniel/docs-api-guide`\n- ✅ `@daniel/refactor-store`\n- ❌ `daniel/docsupdatedelegation-statusskilltomatchactualapistructure` (too verbose, missing @)\n- ❌ `@daniel/add-caching` (should be `feat-caching` or `chore-caching`)\n\n**Avoid:**\n- Excessive detail in branch names\n- Missing the `@daniel/` prefix\n\n### Branch Renaming\nIf a branch is **not yet pushed to remote**, rename it to comply with the naming convention above before pushing.\n\n## Images\n\nWhen a user attaches an image that is stored in a temporary location (e.g. `/tmp/`, `/var/folders/`, macOS screenshot capture directories like `TemporaryItems/NSIRD_screencaptureui_*/`, or any other path that may be cleared), always copy it to the current working directory or a user-specified destination before proceeding. Do not reference or work with images solely from their tmp path — they will be lost when the session ends.\n\n## Markdown\n\n### Diagrams\n\nWhen generating diagrams in markdown files, always use [Mermaid](https://mermaid.js.org/) syntax (fenced code blocks with `mermaid` as the language identifier).\n\n- Do **not** use `\\n` inside node labels for line breaks — it is not valid Mermaid syntax. Use `<br/>` for line breaks within node text instead.\n\n--- project-doc ---\n\n# CLAUDE.md\n\nThis file provides guidance to Claude Code (claude.ai/code) when working with code in this repository.\n\n## Repository Overview\n\nRainbow is a cryptocurrency wallet browser extension built with TypeScript, React, and Manifest V3. It supports multiple blockchain networks, hardware wallets, and provides a comprehensive DeFi experience.\n\n## Common Development Commands\n\n### Setup & Installation\n\n```bash\nyarn install\nyarn setup\n```\n\n### Development\n\n```bash\nyarn dev    # development build with hot reload\nyarn build  # production build\n```\n\n### Testing\n\nThe test runner is **vitest** (not jest).\n\n```bash\nyarn test                          # run all unit tests\nyarn test path/to/file.test.ts     # run a single unit test file\nyarn test:watch                    # watch mode\n\n# E2E tests (requires yarn build first)\nyarn e2e:parallel\nyarn e2e:serial\nyarn e2e:swap\nyarn e2e:send\nyarn e2e:send:optimism\nyarn e2e:dappInteractions\n\n# Run a single E2E test file\nvitest --config ./e2e/vitest.config.ts e2e/serial/send/1_sendFlow.test.ts\n```\n\n### Code Quality\n\n```bash\nyarn lint       # ESLint (max-warnings: 0)\nyarn typecheck  # TypeScript check\n```\n\n### Other\n\n```bash\nyarn graphql-codegen  # regenerate GraphQL types from schema\nyarn ds               # design system dev server\nyarn ds:build         # build design system\n```\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\n### Entry Points (`/src/entries/`)\n\n- **background/**: Service worker — extension lifecycle, wallet management, message routing, oRPC procedures\n- **popup/**: Main React UI — routing, wallet management, DeFi features\n- **content/**: Script injected into web pages for dApp communication\n- **inpage/**: EIP-1193 provider injected into page context for Web3 interactions\n- **iframe/**: Isolated frame for secure transaction approvals\n\nAll entry points call `lockdown()` for security before initializing.\n\n### Core Systems (`/src/core/`)\n\n- **keychain/**: Cryptographic key management, wallet generation, hardware wallet integration (WebUSB/HID)\n- **state/**: Zustand stores — wallets, transactions, settings, assets, networks, NFTs, favorites\n- **resources/**: React Query-based API resources for blockchain data\n- **network/**: HTTP clients for Rainbow backend, GraphQL, and blockchain providers\n- **viem/**: Ethereum interaction layer with provider management\n- **messengers/**: Cross-context communication system (see below)\n- **raps/**: Rainbow Action Protocol — composable transaction flows (see below)\n- **graphql/**: GraphQL queries and codegen output\n\n### State Management\n\nUses `createBaseStore` from `@storesjs/stores` with a custom `createExtensionStoreOptions` wrapper that adds:\n\n- Chrome storage persistence (key prefix `'rainbow.zustand.'`) with throttled writes\n- Schema versioning and migration system\n- Full TypeScript type inference\n\n### Messengers (`/src/core/messengers/`)\n\n`initializeMessenger({ connect: 'background' | 'inpage' | ... })` auto-detects the calling script context and returns the appropriate messenger:\n\n- **extensionMessenger** — popup ↔ background\n- **tabMessenger** — content ↔ background\n- **windowMessenger** — content ↔ inpage\n- **bridgeMessenger** — popup/background ↔ inpage\n\nBackground→popup connections wrap handlers with `withOriginValidation()` to prevent cross-origin message handler bypass.\n\nAPI: `messenger.send(topic, payload)` / `messenger.reply(topic, callback)`\n\n### RAPs (`/src/core/raps/`)\n\nRainbow Action Protocol enables composable multi-step transaction flows:\n\n- **Actions** (`actions/`): Atomic operations — `unlock`, `swap`, `crosschainSwap`\n- **Composites**: `unlockAndSwap.ts`, `unlockAndCrosschainSwap.ts`\n- **Execution** (`execute.ts`): `createSwapRapByType` + `runAction` with prepare → execute phases\n- Integrates with `@rainbow-me/delegation` for batched transactions\n\n### Security Architecture\n\n- Manifest V3 provides runtime isolation and CSP-based network firewall\n- LavaMoat protects build process from supply chain attacks\n- Encrypted keychain storage using browser-passworder\n\n## Key Development Patterns\n\n### Import Paths\n\nUse `~/` alias for internal imports (e.g., `~/core/types/assets`). Configured in `tsconfig.json`.\n\n### Component Development\n\n- Popup components: `/src/entries/popup/components/`\n- Design System components: `/src/design-system/components/`\n- Styling: Vanilla Extract (`.css.ts` files) — zero-runtime CSS-in-JS\n- Design system docs: `.docs.tsx` files alongside components\n\n### oRPC Error Handling\n\noRPC is used for background ↔ popup RPC. Contracts live in `src/entries/background/contracts/`, handlers in `src/entries/popup/handlers/`.\n\n**Server (contracts + handlers):**\n- Define failures on the contract: `.errors({ CODE: { data: z… } })`\n- In handlers, throw `errors.CODE({ data })` — not raw `Error` for UI-handled cases\n- Middleware in `procedures/popup/index.ts` must pass through defined `ORPCError`s (no swallowing)\n\n**Client (popup components):**\n- Use `safe(popupClient.wallet.procedureName(input))` — call `safe` on the procedure promise directly, not on a wrapper that unwraps output (loses contract error types)\n- `const [err, data, isDefined] = await safe(promise)`\n- Multiple `.errors()` codes → branch on `err.code` (not just `isDefined`)\n- Addresses from RPC/errors: always `getAddress(...)` before storage — avoid `as Address`\n\n### Working with Blockchain Data\n\n- Fetch data via resources in `/src/core/resources/`\n- Complex transaction flows via RAPs in `/src/core/raps/`\n- Network configuration in `/src/core/state/networks/`\n\n### Testing\n\n- Unit tests are colocated with source files (`*.test.ts`)\n- E2E tests split into `/e2e/parallel/` (independent) and `/e2e/serial/` (ordered) suites\n- Test helpers: `/e2e/helpers.ts`; mock data: `/e2e/mocks/`\n\n## PR Instructions\n\n- Prefix commits and PR titles with a conventional type: `fix:`, `feat:`, `chore:`, etc.\n- Never modify any `CHANGELOG.md` files — managed automatically.\n- Only modify `en-US.json` locale files; never edit other